[{"id":"VH950267","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH949937.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following claims is correct for the electric field at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and gives a correct physical reason to support this claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH950267_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of two concentric rings. Â The larger ring has a radius of R and the smaller ring has a radius of R over 2. Point P is shown at a distance of x from the center of the rings along an axis through their center that is perpendicular to the plane of the rings.\" height=\"228\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH949937.g01.png\" width=\"210\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Two concentric rings each carry a charge of magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow></math></span></span>. The larger ring of radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\"><math alttext=\"R\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has a positive charge. The smaller ring of radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R over 2\"><math alttext=\"R over 2\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has a negative charge. Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from the center of the rings along an axis through their center.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is zero, because the two rings have equal and opposite charges.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> will be to the left, because the electric field from the larger ring will be larger in magnitude.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> will be to the left, because the electric field from the smaller ring will be larger in magnitude.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> will be to the right, because the electric field from the larger ring will be larger in magnitude.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric field at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>P</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> will be to the right, because the electric field from the smaller ring will be larger in magnitude.</p>"],"answer":2}]